{"title_page": "List of Tyne and Wear Metro stations", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2015}}\n[[File:Tyne & Wear Metro diagram.png|right|thumb|335px|A schematic map of the Tyne and Wear Metro system.]]\nThe following is a list of [[Tyne and Wear Metro]] stations.\n\n==Purpose-built stations==\nThe following stations were built specifically for the Tyne and Wear Metro system.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Station !! Opening date\n|-\n| {{metro|Newcastle Airport|x}} || {{date|1991-11-17}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Bank Foot|x}} || {{date|1981-05-10}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Bede|x}} || {{date|1984-03-24}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Byker|x}} || {{date|1982-11-14}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Callerton Parkway|x}} || {{date|1991-11-17}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Central Station|x}} || {{date|1981-11-15}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Chichester|x}} || {{date|1984-03-24}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Chillingham Road|x}} || {{date|1982-11-14}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Fawdon|x}} || {{date|1981-05-10}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Fellgate|x}} || {{date|2002-03-31}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Four Lane Ends|x}} || {{date|1980-08-11}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Gateshead|x}} || {{date|1981-11-15}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Gateshead Stadium|x}} <ref group=note>Called '''Old Fold''' dueing the planning stages.</ref>|| {{date|1981-11-15}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Hadrian Road|x}} || {{date|1982-11-14}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Haymarket|x}} || {{date|1980-08-11}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Heworth|x}} || {{date|1981-11-15}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Ilford Road|x}} || {{date|1980-08-11}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Jesmond|x}} || {{date|1980-08-11}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Kingston Park|x}} || {{date|1985-09-15}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Manors|x}} || {{date|1982-11-14}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Meadow Well|x}} <ref group=note>Opened as '''Smiths Park''', renamed as '''Meadow Well''' on 10 October 1994.</ref> || {{date|1982-11-14}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Millfield|x}} || {{date|2002-03-31}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Monument|x}} || {{date|1981-11-15}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Northumberland Park|x}} || {{date|2005-12-11}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Pallion|x}} || {{date|2002-03-31}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Palmersville|x}} || {{date|1986-03-19}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Park Lane|x}} || {{date|2002-03-31}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Pelaw|x}} <ref group=note>A previous station named '''Pelaw''' opened on 18 November 1896, but was located north of the Metro station site.</ref> || {{date|1985-09-16}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Regent Centre|x}} || {{date|1981-05-10}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Simonside|x}} || {{date|2008-03-17}}\n|-\n| {{metro|St James|x}} || {{date|1982-11-14}}\n|-\n| {{metro|St Peter's|x}} || {{date|2002-03-31}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Shiremoor|x}} || {{date|1980-08-11}}\n|-\n| {{metro|South Hylton|x}} || {{date|2002-03-31}}\n|-\n| {{metro|South Shields|x}} || {{date|1984-03-24}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Stadium of Light|x}} || {{date|2002-03-31}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Tyne Dock|x}} || {{date|1984-03-24}}\n|-\n| {{metro|University|x}} || {{date|2002-03-31}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Wansbeck Road|x}} || {{date|1981-05-10}}\n|}\n\n==Converted stations==\n[[File:Tynemouth station Metro train.jpg|thumb|right|250px|A metro train for St James arrives at Tynemouth station]]\nThese stations were built prior to the Metro system, but have since been converted or re-built for Metro use. All except Sunderland now serve Metro trains only.\n\nThis list does not include Fawdon, Bank Foot, and Regent Centre, which are located on the sites of the former Coxlodge, Kenton, and West Gosforth stations on what was once the [[Ponteland Railway]], but which closed to passenger traffic in 1929; Pelaw, which was added to the Metro in 1985, and which is sited to the south of the former station of that name; Northumberland Park, opened 2005, built on the approximate site of the previous [[Backworth]] station, closed in 1979; and Palmersville, added in 1985, close to the short-lived Benton Square station (which was open 1909-1915). In addition, Jesmond, Manors, and Central Station are all purpose-built underground stations that were built near to, and share names with, previous suburban stations, and South Shields is built upon a bridge closer to the town centre than the previous mainline station of that name.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Station !! Opening date !! Metro since\n|-\n| {{metro|Benton|x}} || {{date|1871-03-01}} || {{date|1980-08-11}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Brockley Whins|x}} <ref group=note>Named '''Boldon Colliery''', 1925{{endash}}1991.</ref>|| {{date|1839-06-19}} || {{date|2002-03-31}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Cullercoats|x}} || {{date|1882-07-07}} || {{date|1980-08-11}}\n|-\n| {{metro|East Boldon|x}} || {{date|1839-06-19}} || {{date|2002-03-31}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Felling|x}} || {{date|1896-11-18}} || {{date|1981-11-15}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Hebburn|x}} || {{date|1839-06-18}} || {{date|1984-03-24}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Howdon|x}} || {{date|}} || {{date|1982-11-14}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Jarrow|x}} || {{date|1872-03-01}} || {{date|1984-03-24}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Longbenton|x}} || {{date|1947-07-14}} || {{date|1980-08-11}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Monkseaton|x}} || {{date|1915-07-25}} || {{date|1980-08-11}}\n|-\n| {{metro|North Shields|x}} || {{date|1839-06-18}} || {{date|1982-11-14}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Percy Main|x}} || {{date|1839-06-18}} || {{date|1982-11-14}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Seaburn|x}} || {{date|1937-05-03}} || {{date|2002-03-31}}\n|-\n| {{metro|South Gosforth|x}} <ref group=note>The old station buildings were demolished in the late 1970s and replaced by the Metro Control Centre</ref> || {{date|1864-06-27}} || {{date|1980-08-11}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Sunderland|x}} || {{date|1879-08-04}} || {{date|2002-03-31}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Tynemouth|x}} || {{date|1882-07-07}} || {{date|1980-08-11}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Walkergate|x}} || {{date|1839-06-18}} || {{date|1982-11-14}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Wallsend|x}} || {{date|1839-06-18}} || {{date|1982-11-14}}\n|-\n| {{metro|West Jesmond|x}} || {{date|1900-12-01}} || {{date|1980-08-11}}\n|-\n| {{metro|West Monkseaton|x}} || {{date|1933-03-02}} || {{date|1980-08-11}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Whitley Bay|x}} || {{date|1910-10-09}} || {{date|1980-08-11}}\n|}\n\n==Proposed stations==\n\nThere have been numerous suggestions for infill stations on the Metro since it opened, and five of these, '''Pelaw''', '''Kingston Park''', '''Palmersville''', '''Northumberland Park''' and '''Simonside''' have been built and attract high patronage. Other plans that have been abandoned or are yet to be built include:\n\n* '''Beaconsfield''' (between Tynemouth and Cullercoats): Proposed in the 1980s, but planned area development was abandoned.\n* '''Dorrington Road''' (west of Fawdon): In the planning stages, would thus probably have been called Fawdon, and today's Fawdon would have been called Coxlodge. The proposed station was sited where the [[A1 road (Great Britain)|Newcastle bypass road]] was ultimately built.\n* '''High Lane Row''' (between Hebburn and Jarrow): Construction to go ahead if the current single track is dualled. Both track dualling and this station are included in the latest proposals to central government.\n* '''Pallion Bridge''' (between South Hylton and Pallion): Proposed to be built when Ford Estate and the former Grove Cranes site are redeveloped for business and residential use, and the [[New Wear Bridge]] is completed, opening up new areas of patronage in the [[Castletown, Sunderland|Castletown]], [[Ford Estate]], Hylton Riverside and Alexandra Park areas.\n* '''Stotts Road''' (between Walkergate and Wallsend): Proposed in the mid-1980s.\n* '''Victoria Road West''' (between Pelaw and Hebburn): Mooted by [[South Tyneside]] government officials in 2008. Currently, this is the longest stretch of track between two stations.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category|Tyne and Wear Metro stations}}\n* {{Cl|Tyne and Wear Metro Green line stations|count=yes}}\n* {{Cl|Tyne and Wear Metro Yellow line stations|count=yes}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of buildings and structures in Tyne and Wear|Metro stations]]\n[[Category:Lists of metro stations|Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:Tyne and Wear Metro stations|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of railway stations in the United Kingdom|Tyne and Wear Metro]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2015}}\n[[File:Tyne and Wear Metro Map.svg|right|thumb|335px|A schematic map of the Tyne and Wear Metro system.]]\nThe following is a list of [[Tyne and Wear Metro]] stations.\n\n==Purpose-built stations==\nThe following stations were built specifically for the Tyne and Wear Metro system.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Station !! Opening date\n|-\n| {{metro|Newcastle Airport|x}} || {{date|1991-11-17}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Bank Foot|x}} || {{date|1981-05-10}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Bede|x}} || {{date|1984-03-24}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Byker|x}} || {{date|1982-11-14}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Callerton Parkway|x}} || {{date|1991-11-17}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Central Station|x}} || {{date|1981-11-15}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Chichester|x}} || {{date|1984-03-24}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Chillingham Road|x}} || {{date|1982-11-14}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Fawdon|x}} || {{date|1981-05-10}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Fellgate|x}} || {{date|2002-03-31}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Four Lane Ends|x}} || {{date|1980-08-11}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Gateshead|x}} || {{date|1981-11-15}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Gateshead Stadium|x}} <ref group=note>Called '''Old Fold''' dueing the planning stages.</ref>|| {{date|1981-11-15}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Hadrian Road|x}} || {{date|1982-11-14}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Haymarket|x}} || {{date|1980-08-11}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Heworth|x}} || {{date|1981-11-15}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Ilford Road|x}} || {{date|1980-08-11}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Jesmond|x}} || {{date|1980-08-11}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Kingston Park|x}} || {{date|1985-09-15}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Manors|x}} || {{date|1982-11-14}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Meadow Well|x}} <ref group=note>Opened as '''Smiths Park''', renamed as '''Meadow Well''' on 10 October 1994.</ref> || {{date|1982-11-14}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Millfield|x}} || {{date|2002-03-31}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Monument|x}} || {{date|1981-11-15}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Northumberland Park|x}} || {{date|2005-12-11}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Pallion|x}} || {{date|2002-03-31}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Palmersville|x}} || {{date|1986-03-19}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Park Lane|x}} || {{date|2002-03-31}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Pelaw|x}} <ref group=note>A previous station named '''Pelaw''' opened on 18 November 1896, but was located north of the Metro station site.</ref> || {{date|1985-09-16}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Regent Centre|x}} || {{date|1981-05-10}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Simonside|x}} || {{date|2008-03-17}}\n|-\n| {{metro|St James|x}} || {{date|1982-11-14}}\n|-\n| {{metro|St Peter's|x}} || {{date|2002-03-31}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Shiremoor|x}} || {{date|1980-08-11}}\n|-\n| {{metro|South Hylton|x}} || {{date|2002-03-31}}\n|-\n| {{metro|South Shields|x}} || {{date|1984-03-24}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Stadium of Light|x}} || {{date|2002-03-31}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Tyne Dock|x}} || {{date|1984-03-24}}\n|-\n| {{metro|University|x}} || {{date|2002-03-31}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Wansbeck Road|x}} || {{date|1981-05-10}}\n|}\n\n==Converted stations==\n[[File:Tynemouth station Metro train.jpg|thumb|right|250px|A metro train for St James arrives at Tynemouth station]]\nThese stations were built prior to the Metro system, but have since been converted or re-built for Metro use. All except Sunderland now serve Metro trains only.\n\nThis list does not include Fawdon, Bank Foot, and Regent Centre, which are located on the sites of the former Coxlodge, Kenton, and West Gosforth stations on what was once the [[Ponteland Railway]], but which closed to passenger traffic in 1929; Pelaw, which was added to the Metro in 1985, and which is sited to the south of the former station of that name; Northumberland Park, opened 2005, built on the approximate site of the previous [[Backworth]] station, closed in 1979; and Palmersville, added in 1985, close to the short-lived Benton Square station (which was open 1909-1915). In addition, Jesmond, Manors, and Central Station are all purpose-built underground stations that were built near to, and share names with, previous suburban stations, and South Shields is built upon a bridge closer to the town centre than the previous mainline station of that name.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Station !! Opening date !! Metro since\n|-\n| {{metro|Benton|x}} || {{date|1871-03-01}} || {{date|1980-08-11}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Brockley Whins|x}} <ref group=note>Named '''Boldon Colliery''', 1925{{endash}}1991.</ref>|| {{date|1839-06-19}} || {{date|2002-03-31}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Cullercoats|x}} || {{date|1882-07-07}} || {{date|1980-08-11}}\n|-\n| {{metro|East Boldon|x}} || {{date|1839-06-19}} || {{date|2002-03-31}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Felling|x}} || {{date|1896-11-18}} || {{date|1981-11-15}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Hebburn|x}} || {{date|1839-06-18}} || {{date|1984-03-24}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Howdon|x}} || {{date|}} || {{date|1982-11-14}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Jarrow|x}} || {{date|1872-03-01}} || {{date|1984-03-24}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Longbenton|x}} || {{date|1947-07-14}} || {{date|1980-08-11}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Monkseaton|x}} || {{date|1915-07-25}} || {{date|1980-08-11}}\n|-\n| {{metro|North Shields|x}} || {{date|1839-06-18}} || {{date|1982-11-14}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Percy Main|x}} || {{date|1839-06-18}} || {{date|1982-11-14}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Seaburn|x}} || {{date|1937-05-03}} || {{date|2002-03-31}}\n|-\n| {{metro|South Gosforth|x}} <ref group=note>The old station buildings were demolished in the late 1970s and replaced by the Metro Control Centre</ref> || {{date|1864-06-27}} || {{date|1980-08-11}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Sunderland|x}} || {{date|1879-08-04}} || {{date|2002-03-31}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Tynemouth|x}} || {{date|1882-07-07}} || {{date|1980-08-11}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Walkergate|x}} || {{date|1839-06-18}} || {{date|1982-11-14}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Wallsend|x}} || {{date|1839-06-18}} || {{date|1982-11-14}}\n|-\n| {{metro|West Jesmond|x}} || {{date|1900-12-01}} || {{date|1980-08-11}}\n|-\n| {{metro|West Monkseaton|x}} || {{date|1933-03-02}} || {{date|1980-08-11}}\n|-\n| {{metro|Whitley Bay|x}} || {{date|1910-10-09}} || {{date|1980-08-11}}\n|}\n\n==Proposed stations==\n\nThere have been numerous suggestions for infill stations on the Metro since it opened, and five of these, '''Pelaw''', '''Kingston Park''', '''Palmersville''', '''Northumberland Park''' and '''Simonside''' have been built and attract high patronage. Other plans that have been abandoned or are yet to be built include:\n\n* '''Beaconsfield''' (between Tynemouth and Cullercoats): Proposed in the 1980s, but planned area development was abandoned.\n* '''Dorrington Road''' (west of Fawdon): In the planning stages, would thus probably have been called Fawdon, and today's Fawdon would have been called Coxlodge. The proposed station was sited where the [[A1 road (Great Britain)|Newcastle bypass road]] was ultimately built.\n* '''High Lane Row''' (between Hebburn and Jarrow): Construction to go ahead if the current single track is dualled. Both track dualling and this station are included in the latest proposals to central government.\n* '''Pallion Bridge''' (between South Hylton and Pallion): Proposed to be built when Ford Estate and the former Grove Cranes site are redeveloped for business and residential use, and the [[New Wear Bridge]] is completed, opening up new areas of patronage in the [[Castletown, Sunderland|Castletown]], [[Ford Estate]], Hylton Riverside and Alexandra Park areas.\n* '''Stotts Road''' (between Walkergate and Wallsend): Proposed in the mid-1980s.\n* '''Victoria Road West''' (between Pelaw and Hebburn): Mooted by [[South Tyneside]] government officials in 2008. Currently, this is the longest stretch of track between two stations.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category|Tyne and Wear Metro stations}}\n* {{Cl|Tyne and Wear Metro Green line stations|count=yes}}\n* {{Cl|Tyne and Wear Metro Yellow line stations|count=yes}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of buildings and structures in Tyne and Wear|Metro stations]]\n[[Category:Lists of metro stations|Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:Tyne and Wear Metro stations|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of railway stations in the United Kingdom|Tyne and Wear Metro]]\n", "name_user": "G-13114", "label": "safe", "comment": "improved map", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Tyne_and_Wear_Metro_stations"}
{"title_page": "Abigail Mason", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{cleanup|reason=needs general tidyup, and additional information|date=April 2014}}\n{{BLP IMDb refimprove|date=July 2014}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n|name = Abigail Mason\n|image = Abigail Mason.jpg\n|caption = Abigail Mason at the 16th Annual MovieGuide Faith and Values Awards Gala\n|occupation = Actress\n}}\n'''Abigail Mason''' is an American actress that has appeared in films and television since 2006.\n\n==Life and career==\nMason was born in [[DeWitt, Michigan]]. She moved to California at the age of 15 to pursue her dreams in entertainment. Since her move, Mason has appeared in projects playing vastly different roles. Some of her more notable roles included playing London's sassy rival on ''[[The Suite Life of Zack & Cody|The Suite Life of Zack and Cody]]'' as well as playing the lead as an amish orphan in Fox's ''[[Saving Sarah Cain]]''.<ref name=IMDB>{{cite web|title=IMDB|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm2211996/|publisher=IMDB}}</ref>  Her role garnished many positive reviews<ref name=\"Move Metropolis\">{{cite web|last=Plath |first=James |title=Saving Sarah Cain - DVD review |url=http://moviemet.com/review/saving-sarah-cain-dvd-review |publisher=Movie Metropolis |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140329081741/http://moviemet.com/review/saving-sarah-cain-dvd-review |archivedate=2014-03-29 }}</ref><ref name=Relevant>{{cite web|last=Swift|first=Bethel|title=Dailies: Saving Sarah Cain|url=http://www.relevantmagazine.com/culture/film/reviews/3637-dailies-saving-sarah-cain|publisher=Relevant Magazine|accessdate=28 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140329093545/http://www.relevantmagazine.com/culture/film/reviews/3637-dailies-saving-sarah-cain|archive-date=29 March 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=Pringle>{{cite web|last=Pringle|first=Darlene|title=Saving Sarah Cain|url=http://www.christiananswers.net/spotlight/movies/2007/savingsarahcain2007.html|publi